Given a string s, check if it can be constructed by taking a substring of it and appending multiple copies of the substring together.
Example 1:
Input: s = "abab"
Output: true
Explanation: It is the substring "ab" twice.

Example 2:
Input: s = "aba"
Output: false

Example 3:
Input: s = "abcabcabcabc"
Output: true
Explanation: It is the substring "abc" four times or the substring "abcabc" twice.



class Solution {
    public boolean repeatedSubstringPattern(String s) {
        String doubled = s + s;
        return doubled.substring(1, doubled.length() - 1).contains(s);
    }
}


// Time: O(n)
// Space: O(n)



Brute force approach:
class Solution {
    public boolean repeatedSubstringPattern(String s) {
        int n = s.length();
        for (int len = 1; len <= n / 2; len++) {
            if (n % len == 0) {
                String sub = s.substring(0, len);
                StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
                for (int i = 0; i < n / len; i++) {
                    sb.append(sub);
                }
                if (sb.toString().equals(s)) return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
}


Dry Run Example: s = "abab"
n = 4
Loop: len = 1 → 2 (since n/2 = 2)
Iteration 1: len = 1
n % len = 4 % 1 = 0 ✅
sub = "a"
Build string: repeat "a" 4 times → "aaaa"
Compare "aaaa".equals("abab") → false ❌
Iteration 2: len = 2
n % len = 4 % 2 = 0 ✅
sub = "ab"
Build string: repeat "ab" 2 times → "abab"
Compare: "abab".equals("abab") → true ✅
Return true.

Time Complexity
Outer loop runs up to n/2 times.
For each valid divisor len, you build a string of length n using StringBuilder.
That takes O(n).
Comparing with s also takes O(n).
So worst case:
O(n2⋅n)=O(n2)

Space Complexity
StringBuilder stores a candidate string of length n.
Substring extraction (s.substring(0, len)) is O(len).
Overall auxiliary space: O(n).
✅ Final Answer
Time Complexity: O(n2)
Space Complexity: O(n)
